Finding an accomodation and getting your immigration bureaucracy done are enough stress, however there are some small things to do to make your first days in Donostia smoother.

Transportation

I'll go over the whole transportation system in Donostia in a future post, but for now, a couple of practical things are the most useful to know:

  • The main mode of transportation inside Donostia is the bus.
  • Use the DBUS app to get the bus time tables. Google Maps is not trn ustworthy in Donostia.
  • On a bus, you can pay by cash, credit or debit card, or a local transportation card.
  • The full bus fare it 1.85€ per ride, as of 2023.
  • If you get a local transportation card, the Mugi Card, you don't have to pay the full fare.
  • There are three types of Mugi Card:
    • Personalized Mugi Card: This one has your name and photo. It takes two weeks to get one. The fare per ride is around 0.60€.
    • Youth Mugi Card: Like the Personalized Mugi Card, but for people under 25. You need empadronamiento for this one. The fare per ride is around 0.40.
    • Anonymous Mugi Card: The most general Mugi Card. You can just buy and use it. The fare per ride is around 0.80.
  • All Mugi Cards cost 5.00€.

So, during your first days in Donostia, it is very convenient to just buy an Anonymous Mugi Card and use it until you figure out how to get one of the other ones.

Where to get the Anonymous Mugi Card?

There are a lot of small shops around Donostia where you can buy and charge a Mugi Card. Just walk around until you see one. If you prefer to know a specific place, I know you can buy them in this small library:

Where to charge your Mugi Card?

  • By cash: in a lot of shops around Donostia. Just walk around and you'll find them.
  • By card:
    • In Kutxabank ATMs
    • In the central bus station
    • In the Euskotren (tram) stations

What about bus lines?

  • Most lines end in Parte Vieja
  • Specifically, they end in the Boulevard just at the entrance of Parte Vieja
  • Lines 5, 25, and 45 get you from the Boulevard to the University of the Basque Country
  • Most bus lines end at 11 PM, except on the weekends, where they go until 2 AM.

SIM

Luckily, it is very easy to get a SIM card in Spain. All you need is your passport, and they only check your personal information (the visa is not relevant for this).

Simply look for a mobile phone store, and they will have prepaid SIM cards you can buy. Use Google Maps with the following inputs:

  • "móvil" (cellphone)
  • "reparación de móvil" (cellphone repair)
  • "tarjeta SIM" (SIM card)
  • and so on.

Then just go with you passport and you should be done in 5 minutes!

Which operator to chose?

Mobile data is very cheap in Spain. Some of the mobile operators we found convenient are:

  • Lebara (their website works really well in English)
  • Orange
  • Vodafone

It is very common to charge your SIM card by cash at a lot of shops in Donostia. Or, you can pay by card online. In my case, I pay 10€ per month for 40GB.

What else?

  • Get a good umbrella, you can find them anywhere. Donostia is the rainiest city in Spain.
  • Find your way to the University of the Basque Country, and to the Informatics Faculty
  • Most probably, you'll arrive around Summer, so you must go to the beach!
